{"text": "(36.18)\n\nNote that \u03b8=\u03c0 at t= \u2212\u221eevolves to \u03b8=0 at t=\u221e. In our choice of gauge the adiabatic eigenstates have real amplitudes,\n\nand therefore the Berry \u201cvector potential\u201d comes out zero. At the same time the non-zero element of the perturbation\n\nmatrix Wnm is\n\nW+\u2212\n\n=\n\ni\n\n\u03b1\n\nE+ \u2212E\u2212\n\n\u00141\n\n2\u03c33\n\n\u0015\n\n+\u2212\n\n=\n\n\u2212i\u03b1 sin(\u03b8)\n\n2\u03a9\n\n=\n\n\u2212i \u03b1\u03ba\n\n2\u03a92\n\n=\n\n\u2212i\n\n2\n\n\u03b1\n\n\u03ba\n\n\u0014\n\n1\n\n(\u03b1t/\u03ba)2 + 1\n\n\u0015\n\n(36.19)\n\nFollowing the standard procedure as in time-dependent perturbation theory we substitute\n\na\u00b1(t)\n\n=\n\nc\u00b1(t) exp\n\n\u0014\n\n\u2212i\n\nZ t\n\nE\u00b1dt\u2032\n\n\u0015\n\n(36.20)\n\nUsing the rescaled variable \u03c4 = \u03b1t/\u03ba, and changing to \u03c4 = sinh(z), the expression for the dynamical phase is\n\n\u03a6(t)\n\n=\n\n\u03ba2\n\n\u03b1\n\nZ \u03c4\n\nd\u03c4\n\np\n\n\u03c4 2 + 1\n\n=\n\n\u03ba2\n\n\u03b1 \u00d7 1\n\n2\n\n\u0012\n\nz + 1\n\n2 sinh(2z)\n\n\u0013\n\n(36.21)\n\nThus for the amplitude c+(t) we get the equation\n\ndc+(t)\n\ndt\n\n=\n\n\u22121\n\n2\n\n\u03b1\n\n\u03ba\n\n\u0014\n\n1\n\n(\u03b1t/\u03ba)2 + 1\n\n\u0015\n\nei\u03a6(t) c\u2212(t)\n\n(36.22)\n\nStarting with the zero order solution (c\u2212(t) 7\u2192\u22121), and performing the time integration, one obtains the first order\n\nadiabatic estimate for the amplitude c+(t), leading to\n\nPLZ\n\n\u2248\n\n1\n\n2\n\nZ \u221e\n\n\u2212\u221e\n\n1\n\n\u03c4 2 + 1 ei\u03a6(\u03c4)d\u03c4\n\n2\n\n=\n\n1\n\n2\n\nZ \u221e\n\n\u2212\u221e\n\n1\n\ncosh(z) ei\u03a6(z)dz\n\n2\n\n(36.23)\n\n182\n\nIn order to evaluate this integral one can use contour integration. The explicit expression for the phase \u03a6 as a function\n\nof z = x + iy is\n\n\u03a6(z)\n\n=\n\n\u03ba2\n\n\u03b1 \u00d7 1\n\n2\n\n\u0014\u0012\n\nx + 1\n\n2 sinh(2x) cos(2y)\n\n\u0013\n\n+ i\n\n\u0012\n\ny + 1\n\n2 cosh(2x) sin(2y)\n\n\u0013\u0015\n\n(36.24)\n\nThe original contour of integration is y = 0, but we would like to deform it into the complex plane so as to get rid of\n\nthe rapid oscillations of the phase factor, and have instead a smooth monotonic variation. The details can be found\n\nin section VI of [arXiv]. The deformed contour is displayed in Fig4 there. The phase is pure imaginary along the\n\ncurves C\u2212and C+. At z0 = 0 + i(\u03c0/2) we have \u03a6 = i(\u03c0/4)\u03ba2/\u03b1, while cosh z \u2248i(z \u2212z0). Consequently we have a\n\npole leading to the same exponent as in the Landau-Zener result. The prefactor come out (\u03c0/3)2.", "embedding": [-0.0059076413, 0.0090854205, 0.015655158, -0.00036544737, -0.018517504, -0.03286799, -0.01891261, -0.013013376, -0.04185083, 0.07294079, 0.019607892, -0.024729323, -0.0016967348, -0.049133684, 0.007890197, 0.033356387, 0.0069601317, -0.019106431, -0.06412674, 0.04790072, 0.0351009, -0.010105594, -0.083393246, -0.009160843, -0.03484124, 0.04675875, 0.014266879, -0.016731052, 0.05593631, 0.055255387, 0.022342432, -0.06468952, 0.004900606, -0.023887157, 0.00047847125, 0.021536719, 0.003570374, -0.019999307, 0.039796732, -0.024739038, 0.035277627, -0.0010840669, -0.0058344053, -0.00885784, -0.025971437, -0.029725341, -0.04001637, 0.00864703, -0.004628402, -0.08303058, 0.0010693222, 0.012231617, 0.021959519, -0.010506667, -0.019737659, -0.007399308, 0.021771802, -0.008612467, -0.031228611, 0.011897553, 0.02943449, -0.004790807, 0.0017603359, -0.03946408, -0.014045911, 0.05458393, -0.010753641, 0.06295623, -0.028938154, -0.041187666, -0.03240701, -0.025520138, 0.0072260466, 0.02908154, -0.071423374, 0.060904868, -0.021449951, -0.02588556, -0.03899131, -0.024492359, -0.024571741, -0.027974095, -0.03157249, 0.0361697, -5.2047366e-05, -0.009402136, -0.0038709408, -0.039966222, 0.025876617, 0.028163647, 0.015079526, 0.06408847, -0.030322257, -0.010995804, 0.021191092, 0.020383308, -0.012582721, 0.032353956, 0.044973664, 0.013566765,